[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating test file inclusion**\n\nI’m wondering if the new file isn’t included because it’s under src/test/java? There might be an issue with JUnit at the top level. Maybe the previous run only tested the Native Image? Since the test file was added after that run, there’s no coverage in the report. We need to refine our understanding of the pipeline. It seems dynamic access reporting might only map generated test files. It’s complicated!\n\n**Investigating coverage issues**\n\nI’m considering if the JaCoCo instrumented class changes could be affecting the constant pool line. The dynamic-agent mentions coverage for active dynamic-access classes, but the direct method on line 42 might not be associated. I can’t call the synthetic class$ method directly because it’s package-private. I’m thinking of alternatives, like loading a fresh copy of the class in a custom classloader from the instrumented jar. However, I might end up pointing to a dependency jar instead. I really need this dynamic access coverage!\n\n**Exploring dynamic access coverage**\n\nI’m thinking of using `javax.activation.MailcapCommandMap.createDataContentHandler(\"text/plain\")` to cover dynamic access without a custom command map. It seems to rely on the library's `META-INF/mailcap` resource, which may trigger ActivationDataFlavor. This could lead to loading the class with Class.forName and initializing the handler in the app loader. I wonder if I should inspect the jar resources to check this out—maybe I’ll just use unzip to see what’s inside!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_049833e0b00739d70169f5144734a881a3aa8e1f2764292551\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp9RRYRKDGWyRzcIBJh8B-jLMzoncvNPLp2ier5YXvcoDUiDYazgOd0CsR1QSfPCSD1Q7a_xTyYhn95CAiu-RwXQ27h2WaVRBaBUgGVSO_WiKmQLRcdJjd3pKNfTRY6rkpdpXWjL2CNweMIsn9HPMZq5M7wBTRq72F4rjkhX8HNOV4mQrH9xYXm8-D-IUme5Jcv2ilJlvH8YKpOWwhX